			<p>
				This project was built by <a href="https://twitter.com/britishnathan">Nathan Johnson</a> and <a href="http://kuanbutts.com/">Kuan Butts</a> during the Fall of 2015. Kuan Butts was sponsored as a Microsoft Civic Technology Fellow in New York City (<a href="https://twitter.com/MicrosoftNY">@MicrosoftNY</a>) and joined up with Nathan, who had been scraping and exploring the <a href="http://bustime.mta.info/wiki/Developers/OneBusAwayRESTfulAPI">MTA's One Bus Away real time bus location data feed</a> since roughly August of 2014. The project involved the creation of a number of tools to handle and calculate aspects of the MTA's bus data. When possible, these tools were generalized to have utliity with any standard GTFS file and all, including the code for this site, are housed under the <a href="https://github.com/Bus-Data-NYC">Bus Data NYC working group</a> on Github.
			</p>
			<p>
				A special thanks to Microsft New York for the generous hosting support. This project runs on a large MySQL database that is running on an Azure Cloud Virtual Machine. It compiles real time data on bus locations of all buses in operation at 30 second intervals, roughly. Daily, it collects and archives 30-second scrapes, running performance metrics calculations as well that allow us to infer arrival and departure times from stops and, consequently, vehicle performance. For more information on the tool, please read <a href="http://kuanbutts.com/">Kuan's blog</a> or reach out to use via the below suggested methods.
			</p>
			<p>
				"Excess Wait Time" is a measure of how much extra time the average passenger waits for a bus compared to how long the schedule suggests they should wait. For a more detailed explanation of this performance metric, read <a href="http://greatergreaterwashington.org/post/2616/bus-on-time-performance-it-matters-what-you-measure/">this</a>.
			</p>

			<h4>
				New Work
			</h4>
			<p>
				The NYC Bus Data API was built to make the MTA's historical Bus Time data more easily accessible to the public. Data available through the API currently covers the time period August 2014 - November 2015. Further data on the performance of New York City local buses is available through a (for now) separate API, about which you can learn more <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1A19OFwvIdE6fVSeqCZ5TdF9JxxnNZpTi07mpf-qBNZQ/pub">here</a> or by viewing the embedded document below. 
